Peel and grate the @ginger{1}. TIP: Use a teaspoon to easily scrape away the peel.

Peel and chop the @sweet potato{1} into 2cm chunks.

Halve the @lime{1/2}.

Heat a drizzle of oil in a large #saucepan{} on medium heat.

Once hot, add the @diced British chicken breast{1%pack}, ginger, @tikka masala paste{75%g} and @tomato puree{30%g}. Stir together and cook for ~{1%min}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and its packaging.

Add in the @sugar{1/2%tsp}, @water{300%ml} for the dal, coconut milk and @vegetable stock paste{15%g}. Stir to combine.

Add the sweet potato and @red split lentils{100%g} to the pan and season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{}.

Bring to a simmer, then cover with a #lid{} and cook until the lentils and sweet potato are soft, ~{20-25%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: The chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Stir occasionally to prevent it from sticking. Add a splash of water if it looks a little dry.

Meanwhile, if you don't have a #toaster{}, heat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7 for the naans.

When the dal has ~{5%minutes} left to cook, cut the @plain naans{2} in half widthways, then put in your toaster until golden.

If you're using the oven, put the naans onto a #baking tray{}. Sprinkle with a little water and pop them into the oven to warm through, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Once toasted, spread over the @butter{20%g}.

Once the dal is cooked, stir through the @baby spinach{40%g} a handful at a time until wilted and piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Squeeze some lime juice into the dal. Taste and add more salt, pepper and more lime juice if needed, adding a splash of water if it's a little thick.

Serve in #bowls{} with the naans alongside for scooping up the dal.

Enjoy!